GIT PRACTICAL: HOOKS + BASIC COMMANDS

---

## PART 1: BASIC GIT OPERATIONS

## Step 1: Initialize Git Repository

cd Desktop/git
git init

## Step 2: Create a File

echo Hello Git > app.txt

## Step 3: Check Repository Status

git status

## Step 4: Stage File

git add app.txt

## Step 5: Commit Changes

git commit -m "First commit"

## Step 6: Modify File

echo Updated content >> app.txt

## Step 7: View Difference

git diff

## Step 8: Commit Updated Changes

git add app.txt
git commit -m "Updated file"

---

## PART 2: GIT HOOKS FOR AUTOMATION

Git hooks are scripts that run automatically during Git events.
They are stored in:
.git/hooks/

---

## Step 1: Navigate to hooks folder

cd .git/hooks

---

## Step 2: Create pre-commit hook (Lint Check)

Create a file named: pre-commit

Add the following code:

#!/bin/sh
echo "Running pre-commit lint check..."

# Check if app.txt is empty

if [ ! -s app.txt ]; then
echo "Error: app.txt is empty!"
exit 1
fi

echo "Lint check passed!"

---

## Step 3: Make hook executable

chmod +x pre-commit

---

## Step 4: Create pre-push hook (Test Check)

Create a file named: pre-push

Add the following code:

#!/bin/sh
echo "Running tests before push..."

# Example test

echo "All tests passed!"

---

## Step 5: Make hook executable

chmod +x pre-push

---

## Step 6: Create post-merge hook

Create a file named: post-merge

Add the following code:

#!/bin/sh
echo "Post-merge action executed!"
echo "You may install dependencies here."

---

## Step 7: Make hook executable

chmod +x post-merge

---

## WORKING

* pre-commit: Runs before every commit
* pre-push: Runs before pushing code
* post-merge: Runs after merging branches

